Aviva, Kesa, Northumbrian Water Group: U.K., Irish Stock Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-06-28T06:42:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-27/bp-plc-kesa-northumbrian-water-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The FTSE 100 Index advanced 24.62 points, or 0.4 percent,
to 5,722.34 yesterday. The FTSE All-Share Index rose 0.4
percent, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index advanced 0.2 percent.  AstraZeneca Plc (AZN)  : Heart patients taking
AstraZeneca’s Brilinta blood-thinner and more than 300
milligrams of aspirin fared worse than those taking Sanofi and
Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.’s Plavix, according to a new analysis
of a study. The stock fell 1.1 percent to 3,026 pence.  Aviva Plc (AV/)  : The U.K.’s second-biggest insurer by
market value was cut to “neutral” from “buy” at Goldman
Sachs Group Inc. The shares fell 0.6 percent to 419.9 pence.  Berkeley Group Holdings Plc (BKG)  : The U.K.’s largest
homebuilder by market value was downgraded to “hold” from
“buy” at Citigroup Inc. The shares jumped 3.6 percent to 1,299
pence.  Kesa Electricals Plc (KESA)  :  Europe ’s third-largest
electronics retailer said its largest shareholder, Knight Vinke
Asset Management LLC, increased its holding in the company to 19
percent. The stock retreated 1 percent to 132.7 pence.  London Stock Exchange Group Plc (LSE)  : Mawer Investment
Management Ltd. voted against London Stock Exchange Group Plc’s
takeover offer for TMX Group Inc. The stock fell 1.1 percent to
937 pence.  Northumbrian Water Group Plc (NWG)  : The U.K. utility’s
board said it hasn’t received any proposal from Cheung Kong
Infrastructure Holdings Ltd. (1038 HK), which had announced that
it is in the preliminary stages of assessing a potential cash
offer for Northumbrian Water. The stock jumped 8 percent to
413.5 pence.  Prudential Plc (PRU)  : The U.K.’s largest insurer was
raised to “buy” from “neutral” at Goldman Sachs. The shares
added 0.7 percent to 687.5 pence.  The brokerage also upgraded  Legal & General Group Plc (LGEN)  , the U.K.’s fourth-biggest insurer by market value, and St.
James’s Place Plc (STJ LN), the wealth manager majority-owned by
Lloyds Banking Group Plc. Legal & General shares slipped 0.4
percent to 109.6 pence, while St James’s Place was little
changed at 319.1 pence.  Scottish & Southern Energy Plc (SSE)  : The U.K.’s second-
biggest power producer and Statoil ASA said all nine natural gas
storage caverns at their Aldbrough site in northern  England  have
been leached. The shares retreated 0.1 percent to 1,391 pence.  Standard Chartered Plc (STAN)  :  The U.K.’s third-largest
bank by market value said first-half profit before tax and
income may post “double-digit” growth from a year earlier. The
shares gained 1.4 percent to 1,540 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
